04287nam a22005895i 9780228005919DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280059197 a10.1515/97802280059192doi  a(DE-B1597)655157  a(OCoLC)1191824304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR431.A45 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a820.92231 aAlker, Sharon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBesieged :bEarly Modern British Siege Literature, 1642-1722 /cSharon Alker, Holly Faith Nelson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe “Talismanic” Siege -- tFacts, Feelings, and Fractured Networks -- tSiege Drama Reimagined -- tSpace Made for Change -- tSongs of War in the Popular Imagination -- tThe Fading Heroic to the Satiric -- tOld Forms, New Discourses -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSiege literature has existed since antiquity but has not always been understood as a crucial element of culture. Focusing on its magnetic force, Besieged brings to light its popularity and potency between the British Civil War and the Great Northern War in Europe, a period in which literary texts reflected an urgent interest in siege mentality and tactics.Exploring the siege as represented in canonical works by Milton, Dryden, Defoe, Davenant, Cowley, Cavendish, and Bunyan, alongside a wide array of little-known memoirs, plays, poems, and works of prose fiction on military and civilian experiences of siege warfare, Besieged breaks new ground in the field of early modern war literature. Sharon Alker and Holly Faith Nelson draw on theories of space and place to show how early modern Britons feverishly worked to make sense of the immediacy, horror, and trauma of urban warfare, offering a valuable perspective on the literature that captured the cultural imagination during and after the traumatic civil wars of the 1640s.Alker and Nelson demonstrate how the narratives of besieged cities became a compelling way to engage with the fragility of urban space, unstable social structures, developing technologies, and the inadequacy of old heroic martial models. Given the reality of urban warfare in our own age, Besieged provides a timely foundation for understanding the history of such spaces and their cultural representation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aMilitary art and science in literature. 0aWar in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aliterary criticism.  amilitary history.1 aNelson, Holly Faith, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228005919?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228005919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228005919/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles